ELK Component – Design and Role in Workflow Event Processing


---

1. Overview

The ELK stack (Elasticsearch, Logstash, Kibana) is used as the centralized platform for storing, indexing, and analyzing workflow events collected from multiple source systems such as CMWS and Amplify.

It enables:

Consolidation of workflow data

Near real-time visibility

Advanced search and analytics

Dashboard-based monitoring



---

2. Purpose of ELK in the Architecture

The primary objectives of using ELK are:

To act as a single source of truth for workflow events

To provide searchable and indexed storage of event data

To enable analytics and visualization of workflow processes

To support downstream systems (e.g., CPM dashboards) via APIs



---

3. Components of ELK

3.1 Elasticsearch

Core storage and indexing engine

Stores events as documents

Supports fast querying and filtering

Uses time-based indices for efficient data management


3.2 Logstash

Data ingestion and processing pipeline

Handles:

Parsing

Transformation

Data masking (where applicable)


Prepares data before indexing into Elasticsearch


3.3 Kibana

Visualization and dashboard layer

Enables:

Real-time monitoring

Workflow analytics

Trend analysis




---

4. Role of ELK in the End-to-End Flow

ELK sits at the final stage of the pipeline and performs the following:

1. Receives processed events from upstream systems (Spring Boot / NiFi / messaging layer)


2. Applies ingestion pipelines (via Logstash or ingest nodes)


3. Indexes events into Elasticsearch


4. Makes data available for querying and visualization through Kibana


5. Exposes data for downstream consumption (e.g., CPM UI)




---

5. Data Flow into ELK

Input Sources

Spring Boot applications (event processing layer)

NiFi (enrichment and routing layer)

Messaging systems (MQ/SQS/Kafka) – if used


Flow

Events are generated and standardized upstream

Events are pushed to ELK ingestion layer

Data is processed and indexed

Indexed data becomes available for search and analytics



---

6. Data Structure and Indexing Strategy

Event Structure (Expected)

Each event indexed in Elasticsearch should include:

document_id

workflow_id / workflow_name

event_type

event_timestamp (source system time)

ingestion_timestamp

user_id

queue (if applicable)

additional metadata (enriched fields)


Indexing Strategy

Time-based indices (e.g., daily or weekly indices)

Index naming convention to be standardized

Support for high-volume ingestion and efficient querying



---

7. Event Time vs Ingestion Time

A key requirement is to maintain:

Event Time: Actual time when the event occurred in the source system

Ingestion Time: Time when the event is processed and stored in ELK


ELK should prioritize event time for:

Accurate sequencing

Correct analytics

Reliable reporting



---

8. Data Masking and Governance

ELK includes a data masking pipeline for sensitive data

However, primary masking should be performed upstream (Spring Boot layer)


Requirements:

Identify PII fields (e.g., email, date of birth)

Ensure masked or filtered data is indexed

Comply with data governance and security policies



---

9. Querying and Search Capabilities

Elasticsearch enables:

Search by document_id

Filtering by workflow, event_type, queue

Time-range queries

Aggregations for analytics


This supports:

Debugging

Audit trails

Process tracking



---

10. Visualization and Analytics (Kibana)

Kibana dashboards provide:

Workflow status monitoring

Queue-level insights

Processing time analysis

Event trends over time


These dashboards enable:

Operational visibility

Business reporting

Performance optimization



---

11. Performance and Scalability

ELK is designed to handle:

High event volumes

Continuous ingestion

Scalable storage


Considerations:

Index lifecycle management (ILM)

Retention policies

Query performance optimization



---

12. Integration with Downstream Systems

ELK acts as a data source for downstream systems, such as:

CPM (Salesforce UI dashboards)

Reporting tools

Monitoring systems


Data can be accessed via:

APIs

Queries

Dashboards



---

13. Key Design Considerations

Ensure standardized event format before ingestion

Maintain consistency across multiple source systems

Handle late-arriving events correctly

Define clear indexing and retention strategy

Ensure PII compliance and data security



---

14. Summary

The ELK stack serves as the central analytics and storage layer in the architecture, enabling consolidation, search, visualization, and analysis of workflow events from multiple systems.

It transforms raw event data into actionable insights, supporting both operational monitoring and business decision-making.


