18. Event Correlation Strategy
Since events come from multiple sources, ELK relies on correlation logic.
Correlation Keys
document_id (case_id)
user_id
timestamp
How It Works
Same action appears in:
Access log (user action)
CDC (system update)
Events are matched using:
Same document
Same user
Time proximity
Outcome
ELK stores a complete timeline of events per document.









6. Data Structure and Indexing Strategy
Event Structure (Standardized)
Events indexed in Elasticsearch should follow a process-mining-ready structure, derived from CDC data and WebSphere access logs.
Each event should include:
case_id (document_id)
Primary identifier used to group all events related to a document
activity (event_type)
Derived from:
workflow_event_cd + event_data1 (CDC – WORKFLOW_HISTORY)
URL patterns (access logs, e.g., /workflow/move.go)
timestamp (event_time)
Actual time when the event occurred in the source system (database or HTTP request time)
resource (user_id)
From CDC (e.g., user_ions_id, modified_by)
From access logs (iv-user header)
source
Indicates origin of event:
CDC (database changes)
access_log (user actions)
workflow/schema
Schema name (e.g., LRKPROD, COBPROD) to distinguish workflows across 21 schemas
additional context fields (if available)
queue name (from DOCUMENT_QUEUE or event_data1)
response status / time (from access logs)






Indexing Strategy
1. Multi-Layer Index Design
To support flexibility and performance, the following index structure is recommended:
Raw Indices
cmws-cdc-events-* (database change events)
cmws-access-logs-* (user interaction logs)
Processed / Unified Index (Primary)
cmws-process-events-*
This index contains normalized and correlated events used for:
Analytics
Dashboards
Process mining
2. Time-Based Indexing
Use time-series indices (e.g., daily indices)
Enables:
Efficient querying
Faster indexing
Easy archival and retention
